#Text=Tennant Creek
#Text=Tennant Creek is a town in the Northern Territory of Australia .
#Text=It has a population of around 3,500 .
#Text=It is known as the Territory ’s heart of gold mainly due to the people , but also in reference to the gold mining history .
#Text=Understand
#Text=Tennant Creek in Central Australia sits on the Explorer ’s Way , 500km north of Alice Springs and 1000km south of Darwin .
#Text=The town is surrounded to the east by the Barkly Tablelands - a huge expanse of land that supports some of Australia ’s premier outback cattle stations .
#Text=Tennant Creek sits in the middle of the outback , but the country is beautiful and anything but barren .
#Text=The town is situated in open mallee scrubland , surrounded by rocky ranges and brilliant blue skies that give way to millions of stars at night .

#Text=Prior to the gold rush era , Tennant Creek ’s first European residents were workers on the Overland Telegraph Line , which established a communication link between Australia and the rest of the world .
#Text=The Telegraph Station was built in 1872 , and this historical collection of stone buildings can be explored today .
#Text=Aboriginal culture is strong in Tennant Creek .

#Text=The traditional land owners of this area are the aboriginal Warumungu people , and they recognise a number of sacred sites in the area , including the region ’s most famous landmark – the Devils Marbles – about 100km south of the town .
#Text=The Pebbles ( known as Kunjarra ) are another granite outcrop formation , just north of the town , and it 's also a sacred site for the Warumungu people .
#Text=The Nyinkka Nyunyu Culture Centre in Tennant Creek is an award-winning aboriginal attraction that showcases the people ’s stories and art .

#Text=The Barkly region is steeped in the ancient traditions and beliefs of its traditional custodians , and around nine Aboriginal groups call the area home , including the Warumungu , Walpiri , Kaiditch and Alyawarr people .
#Text=The air is fresh and clean here and the colours of the landscape are ever-changing as the rocky hillsides pick up the varying sun 's rays between daybreak and evening .
#Text=A number of walking trails throughout the region allow travellers to experience the plants , birds and landscapes of Tennant Creek up close .
#Text=One walking path winds its way through the Honeymoon Ranges to Lake Mary Ann , five kilometres north-east of the town , and the perfect spot for a swim and a picnic .
#Text=Adventure lovers have plenty of options in the Tennant Creek area .
#Text=Four-wheel-drivers in particular are spoilt for choice with the plethora of moderate to challenging tracks available to test their skills and their vehicles .
#Text=The Davenport Range National Park is an excellent four-wheel-drive destination and there are plenty of nooks and crannies to explore .

#Text=The Old Police Station Waterhole , located on the Frew River , is the park 's best known attraction , and the moderately challenging Frew River Four Wheel Drive Loop Track is an exciting alternative route in .
#Text=It 's a rocky , 17-kilometre track with several kilometres along the ridgeline , which affords spectacular vistas .
#Text=This is just one of the four-wheel-drive tracks in the region .
#Text=Camping in Tennant Creek is an adventure in itself .

#Text=There are caravan parks and camp grounds in town , but for a real feeling of isolation , where there are no creature comforts , pack up the car and try one of the region 's bush camping sites in the peace and quiet of the outback - make sure you take all your own supplies .
#Text=Why not aim to go home in style after you discover your fortune in Tennant Creek ?
#Text=There are a number of sites in this area where people can fossick for their own gold - and apparently there 's still plenty here to be found .
#Text=Another adventurous pursuit in this area is experiencing life on an outback cattle station .
#Text=Travellers can camp at Banka Banka Station , an operating station 100km to the town 's north .
#Text=By plane
#Text=Tennant Creek has an airfield , and charter flights are easily arranged from either Darwin or Alice Springs .
#Text=Tiwi Air has some scheduled services from Darwin .
#Text=By car
#Text=Cars can be hired at Alice Springs or Darwin .
#Text=It is possible to hire at one and drop off at the other for a fee , but probably best to check with the company beforehand .
#Text=Tennant Creek is 500km north along the Stuart Highway from Alice Springs and 1000km due south from Darwin .
#Text=Car rental companies in the Northern Territory have daily distance allowances after which a surcharge is payable ;
#Text=however , if you book with the government wholesaler , Territory Discoveries , you can get unlimited rates .
#Text=By bus
#Text=Greyhound services the highway between Adelaide and Darwin , with a stop in Alice Springs .
#Text=Northbound the coach arrives in Tennant Creek at 2.10AM , and departs at 3.25AM .
#Text=Southbound , it 's a similar time , with the coach arriving at 2.30AM and departing at 3.45AM .
#Text=By train
#Text=The Ghan , running on the famous Adelaide-Darwin route , passes by Tennant Creek twice each way per week and will stop on request .
#Text=Serious enthusiasm for train travel is required to book in advance , arrive at 2AM in the morning , and then catch the next onward train out at 2AM three or four days later .
#Text=The Ghan , being a tourist train rather than a regular form of transport , also charges a significant premium to the bus , and takes considerably longer .
#Text=Get around
#Text=The town itself is relatively small and everything within the town can be reached on foot .
#Text=A car is needed to reach attractions slightly further afield .
#Text=See
#Text=Tennant Creek Museum at Tuxworth Fullwood House , Schmidt St , ☏ +61889812848 .
#Text=Built by the Army in 1942 as No. 45 Australian Camp Hospital , the building now features a wide range of exhibits , including a 1930s police cell and steam traction engine .
#Text=It also houses a reconstruction of a miner 's camp and mine workings , a Furphy water cart , an extensive archive and early photographs of the town and its people .
#Text=Entry fees apply .
#Text=Winanjjikari Music Centre , 52 Peko Road , Tennant Creek , ☏ +61889623282 .
#Text=The Winanjjikari Music Centre offers a profound cultural exchange with authentic , traditional Aboriginal people .
#Text=You ’re welcome to come and see the daily life of the musicians , have a chat with them and even join in a song .
#Text=Free entry .
#Text=Tennant Creek Telegraph Station , Stuart Highway ( 10km north of Tennant Creek ) , ☏ +61889518250 .
#Text=Built in 1872 the Tennant Creek Telegraph Station offered a refuge for weary travellers .
#Text=The discovery of gold by a linesman in 1925 quickly led to the establishment of the present Tennant Creek township .
#Text=By 1935 a post office was opened which quickly led to the closure of the telegraph station , ending an era of hospitality for weary travellers .
#Text=Free entry .
#Text=Nyinkka Nyunyu Interpretive Centre , Paterson Street ( Stuart Highway ) , ☏ +61889622221 .

#Text=Nyinkka Nyunyu ( pronounced ny-ink-a ny-oo ny-oo ) is a fascinating and unique art , culture and interpretive centre , which offers visitors the opportunity to learn about Aboriginal life , history and land in the Tennant Creek region .
#Text=Entry fees apply .
#Text=Bill Allen Lookout ( off Peko Road , just east of town ) .
#Text=Offers a clear 360-degree view across the landscape and town - it 's especially worthwhile to do this at sundown .
#Text=Kunjarra ( The Pebbles ) , Off Stuart Highway ( 10km north of town , the dirt road starts opposite the Telegraph Station ) .
#Text=Smaller and less interesting relatives of the Devils Marbles , but much closer to Tennant Creek .
#Text=Known to the Warumungu Aboriginal people as Kunjarra , The Pebbles are a sacred site and women ’s dancing place for the Munga Munga Dreaming .
